<Document>
<name>Historic Columbia River Highway</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Historic Columbia River Highway</h2><p><i>Oregon, USA · US-30 historic route, Troutdale to The Dalles</i></p><p><b>America's first scenic highway: 1916 stonework, Multnomah Falls, the Columbia River Gorge.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>103 km (64 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>4–5 hrs with stops</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>April–October (waterfalls thunder in spring; fall foliage early Oct)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Crowds at Multnomah Falls; ice in winter; some sections still closed from 2017 Eagle Creek fire</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>162</td></tr></table><hr><p>Engineer Samuel Lancaster set out in 1913 to build a road that 'would not mar what God had put there.' What opened in 1916 was the first scenic highway in America — hand-laid stone retaining walls, Italian stonemason-built guard rails, viaducts that follow the rim rather than blast through it. Bypassed by I-84 in the 1950s and largely forgotten until restoration began in the 1980s. Most of it is now reopened to cars; the 2017 Eagle Creek wildfire damaged some sections still being rebuilt. Drive the historic road wherever it's open; use I-84 to fill the gaps.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Vista House at Crown Point</b> — 1918 octagonal observatory at 222 m above the river — built explicitly as 'a memorial to the pioneers' and 'a place for travelers to rest.' Free.</li><li><b>Multnomah Falls</b> — 189 m, second-tallest year-round waterfall in the US. Two-tiered drop with the 1914 Benson Bridge spanning the gap. Crowded; reservations required May–Sept.</li><li><b>Oneonta Gorge</b> — Slot canyon you wade up — currently closed for restoration after the 2017 fire. Check status; when open, unforgettable.</li><li><b>Bonneville Dam &amp; Fish Hatchery</b> — 1937 New Deal dam. Underwater fish ladders viewable; Herman the 70-year-old, 3 m sturgeon lives at the hatchery.</li><li><b>Bridge of the Gods</b> — Where the Pacific Crest Trail crosses the Columbia, named for a Native legend of a stone arch that once spanned the river (geologically real — a landslide ~1450 CE).</li><li><b>Rowena Crest</b> — Tight figure-eight loops on the historic highway with balsamroot wildflower meadows above (peak late April).</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
